6,0.12677376,-0.00546936,-0.02754534,0.01139368,-0.01004893,0.01552807,-0.02734121,0.00872309,-0.01513424,0.04262342,0.03331136,-0.02008508,-0.00369685,0.03511980,-0.04751993,0.02882620,0.02139815,0.01619375,-0.03919446,0.02930685,-0.01810087,0.03552523,0.02604738,-0.02478663,-0.01178086,-0.03364110,-0.00384691,-0.01308920,-0.06497180,-0.03480880,0.03011196,0.00886083,0.01155137,0.03850904,0.01921544,0.03629943,-0.00180497,0.08199694,0.07167564,-0.01016448,0.12778804,0.07177584,0.00729293]',E'Installation\n\nIn order to build a Phoenix application, we will need a few dependencies installed in our Operating System:\n\n  * the Erlang VM and the Elixir programming language\n  * a database - Phoenix recommends PostgreSQL, but you can pick others or not use a database at all\n  * and other optional packages.\n\nPlease take a look at this list and make sure to install anything necessary for your system. Having dependencies installed in advance can prevent frustrating problems later on.\n\nIf you just want to get started quickly, the [Up and Running](up_and_running.md) page includes a link to Phoenix Express, which will get Erlang, Elixir and Phoenix installed and running in seconds.','{"source": "phoenix", "version": "1.7", "language": "elixir", "title": "Installation", "section_title": "installation", "url": "https://github.com/phoenixframework/phoenix/blob/main/guides/introduction/installation.md", "topics": "phoenix,elixir,installation", "categories": "web,elixir,fullstack,realtime"}');
