416907,-0.00682288,0.00963368,0.00957281,0.03513545,-0.00743844,-0.06853390,-0.04468914,0.07804299,0.00094778,-0.07098457,0.02011553,-0.00068891,-0.00788219,-0.01657791,0.00804513,-0.00148447,-0.02038739,0.08541920,-0.04891994,0.01594901,-0.00365011,-0.02253872,-0.01120261,-0.02309350,-0.04957342,0.00304260,-0.05041894,-0.04558424,0.00451790,0.02076749,0.04522493,0.03806393,-0.03767385,-0.00216680,-0.03547590,0.00202704,0.08730182,-0.01204863,0.12981309,0.03163537,0.07031207]',E'Phoenix\n\nTo check that we are on Elixir 1.17 and Erlang 25 or later, run:\n\n```console\nelixir -v\nErlang/OTP 25 [erts-13.0] [source] [64-bit] [smp:8:8] [async-threads:10] [hipe] [kernel-poll:false] [dtrace]\n\nElixir 1.17.0\n```\n\nOnce we have Elixir and Erlang, we are ready to install the Phoenix application generator:\n\n```console\n$ mix archive.install hex phx_new\n```\n\nThe `phx.new` generator is now available to generate new applications in the next guide, called [Up and Running](up_and_running.html). The flags mentioned below are command line options to the generator; see all available options by calling `mix help phx.new`.','{"source": "phoenix", "version": "1.7", "language": "elixir", "title": "Installation", "section_title": "installation", "url": "https://github.com/phoenixframework/phoenix/blob/main/guides/introduction/installation.md", "topics": "phoenix,elixir,installation", "categories": "web,elixir,fullstack,realtime"}');
