4501826,-0.04866505,0.00264105,0.03167331,-0.02509277,-0.04904777,0.09169322,-0.01257719,-0.00812586,-0.03247615,0.07890854,0.04166309,0.02017043,0.00050511,-0.05503863,-0.02225371,0.00856288,-0.03979526,-0.07894630,0.08155271,-0.02424691,0.00700064,-0.03123874,-0.01570095,-0.01917681,0.05900663,-0.00669517,-0.01003920,-0.00559359,0.03574421,-0.02518077,-0.00561346,0.06770245,0.04609991,-0.03873844,0.01071508,0.01587402,0.03232392,-0.01311746,0.06589595,0.09551202,0.04362325,0.05826139]',E'Rendering\n\nControllers can render content in several ways. The simplest is to render some plain text using the [`text/2`] function which Phoenix provides.\n\nFor example, let''s rewrite the `show` action from `HelloController` to return text instead. For that, we could do the following.\n\n```elixir\ndef show(conn, %{"messenger" => messenger}) do\n  text(conn, "From messenger #{messenger}")\nend\n```\n\nNow [`/hello/Frank`] in your browser should display `From messenger Frank` as plain text without any HTML.','{"source": "phoenix", "version": "1.7", "language": "elixir", "title": "Controllers", "section_title": "controllers", "url": "https://github.com/phoenixframework/phoenix/blob/main/guides/controllers.md", "topics": "phoenix,elixir,controllers", "categories": "web,elixir,fullstack,realtime"}');
